(lp3
VJust over a year ago,
p4
aVfor the third time in my life, I ceased to exist.
p5
aVI was having a small operation, and my brain was filling with anesthetic.
p6
aVI remember a sense of detachment and falling apart
p7
aVand a coldness.
p8
aVAnd then I was back, drowsy and disoriented,
p9
aVbut definitely there.
p10
aVNow, when you wake from a deep sleep,
p11
aVyou might feel confused about the time or anxious about oversleeping,
p12
aVbut there's always a basic sense of time having passed,
p13
aVof a continuity between then and now.
p14
aVComing round from anesthesia is very different.
p15
aVI could have been under for five minutes, five hours,
p16
aVfive years or even 50 years.
p17
aVI simply wasn't there.
p18
aVIt was total oblivion.
p19
aVAnesthesia \u2014 it's a modern kind of magic.
p20
aVIt turns people into objects,
p21
aVand then, we hope, back again into people.
p22
aVAnd in this process
p23
aVis one of the greatest remaining mysteries in science and philosophy.
p24
aa(lp25
VHow does consciousness happen?
p26
aVSomehow, within each of our brains,
p27
aVthe combined activity of many billions of neurons,
p28
aVeach one a tiny biological machine,
p29
aVis generating a conscious experience.
p30
aVAnd not just any conscious experience \u2014
p31
aVyour conscious experience right here and right now.
p32
aVHow does this happen?
p33
aa(lp34
VAnswering this question is so important
p35
aVbecause consciousness for each of us is all there is.
p36
aVWithout it there's no world,
p37
aVthere's no self,
p38
aVthere's nothing at all.
p39
aVAnd when we suffer, we suffer consciously
p40
aVwhether it's through mental illness or pain.
p41
aVAnd if we can experience joy and suffering,
p42
aVwhat about other animals?
p43
aVMight they be conscious, too?
p44
aVDo they also have a sense of self?
p45
aVAnd as computers get faster and smarter,
p46
aVmaybe there will come a point, maybe not too far away,
p47
aVwhen my iPhone develops a sense of its own existence.
p48
aa(lp49
VI actually think the prospects for a conscious AI are pretty remote.
p50
aVAnd I think this because my research is telling me
p51
aVthat consciousness has less to do with pure intelligence
p52
aVand more to do with our nature as living and breathing organisms.
p53
aVConsciousness and intelligence are very different things.
p54
aVYou don't have to be smart to suffer, but you probably do have to be alive.
p55
aa(lp56
VIn the story I'm going to tell you,
p57
aVour conscious experiences of the world around us,
p58
aVand of ourselves within it,
p59
aVare kinds of controlled hallucinations
p60
aVthat happen with, through and because of our living bodies.
p61
aa(lp62
VNow, you might have heard that we know nothing
p63
aVabout how the brain and body give rise to consciousness.
p64
aVSome people even say it's beyond the reach of science altogether.
p65
aVBut in fact,
p66
aVthe last 25 years have seen an explosion of scientific work in this area.
p67
aVIf you come to my lab at the University of Sussex,
p68
aVyou'll find scientists from all different disciplines
p69
aVand sometimes even philosophers.
p70
aVAll of us together trying to understand how consciousness happens
p71
aVand what happens when it goes wrong.
p72
aVAnd the strategy is very simple.
p73
aVI'd like you to think about consciousness
p74
aVin the way that we've come to think about life.
p75
aVAt one time, people thought the property of being alive
p76
aVcould not be explained by physics and chemistry \u2014
p77
aVthat life had to be more than just mechanism.
p78
aVBut people no longer think that.
p79
aVAs biologists got on with the job
p80
aVof explaining the properties of living systems
p81
aVin terms of physics and chemistry \u2014
p82
aVthings like metabolism, reproduction, homeostasis \u2014
p83
aVthe basic mystery of what life is started to fade away,
p84
aVand people didn't propose any more magical solutions,
p85
aVlike a force of life or an élan vital.
p86
aVSo as with life, so with consciousness.
p87
aVOnce we start explaining its properties
p88
aVin terms of things happening inside brains and bodies,
p89
aVthe apparently insoluble mystery of what consciousness is
p90
aVshould start to fade away.
p91
aVAt least that's the plan.
p92
aa(lp93
VSo let's get started.
p94
aVWhat are the properties of consciousness?
p95
aVWhat should a science of consciousness try to explain?
p96
aVWell, for today I'd just like to think of consciousness in two different ways.
p97
aVThere are experiences of the world around us,
p98
aVfull of sights, sounds and smells,
p99
aVthere's multisensory, panoramic, 3D, fully immersive inner movie.
p100
aVAnd then there's conscious self.
p101
aVThe specific experience of being you or being me.
p102
aVThe lead character in this inner movie,
p103
aVand probably the aspect of consciousness we all cling to most tightly.
p104
aVLet's start with experiences of the world around us,
p105
aVand with the important idea of the brain as a prediction engine.
p106
aa(lp107
VImagine being a brain.
p108
aVYou're locked inside a bony skull,
p109
aVtrying to figure what's out there in the world.
p110
aVThere's no lights inside the skull. There's no sound either.
p111
aVAll you've got to go on is streams of electrical impulses
p112
aVwhich are only indirectly related to things in the world,
p113
aVwhatever they may be.
p114
aVSo perception \u2014 figuring out what's there \u2014
p115
aVhas to be a process of informed guesswork
p116
aVin which the brain combines these sensory signals
p117
aVwith its prior expectations or beliefs about the way the world is
p118
aVto form its best guess of what caused those signals.
p119
aVThe brain doesn't hear sound or see light.
p120
aVWhat we perceive is its best guess of what's out there in the world.
p121
aa(lp122
VLet me give you a couple of examples of all this.
p123
aVYou might have seen this illusion before,
p124
aVbut I'd like you to think about it in a new way.
p125
aVIf you look at those two patches, A and B,
p126
aVthey should look to you to be very different shades of gray, right?
p127
aVBut they are in fact exactly the same shade.
p128
aVAnd I can illustrate this.
p129
aVIf I put up a second version of the image here
p130
aVand join the two patches with a gray-colored bar,
p131
aVyou can see there's no difference.
p132
aVIt's exactly the same shade of gray.
p133
aVAnd if you still don't believe me,
p134
aVI'll bring the bar across and join them up.
p135
aVIt's a single colored block of gray, there's no difference at all.
p136
aVThis isn't any kind of magic trick.
p137
aVIt's the same shade of gray,
p138
aVbut take it away again, and it looks different.
p139
aVSo what's happening here
p140
aVis that the brain is using its prior expectations
p141
aVbuilt deeply into the circuits of the visual cortex
p142
aVthat a cast shadow dims the appearance of a surface,
p143
aVso that we see B as lighter than it really is.
p144
aa(lp145
VHere's one more example,
p146
aVwhich shows just how quickly the brain can use new predictions
p147
aVto change what we consciously experience.
p148
aVHave a listen to this.
p149
